        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 30/77</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am extremely obliged for your letter &amp; the accounts which make everything intelligible to me.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>As I was very glad to get the “Orchids” published at <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> profits it w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be very shabby in me to accept your offer now.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I think you are mistaken in supposing that I asked to be paid before the editions were sold off, &amp; I feel almost sure that you must have misunderstood me. However this is now quite immaterial.</p>
<p>The plan which you say you generally follow with authors seems to me the fairest for both of us, &amp; I fully agree to it.</p>
<p>Again accept my thanks for your letter &amp; documents &amp; I remain | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
